PSEUDOMONAS FOLLICULITIS - UK (SCOTLAND)
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail, a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Thu, 1 Apr 2004
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <arodriguezm@SaludFMV.org>
Source: Scotman News Health, Scotland [edited]
<http://news.scotsman.com/health.cfm?id=371452004>

Pool closed after danger bug scare
-----------------------------------
A swimming center has been closed after several pool users started
developing skin rashes. Fauldhouse Swimming Pool in West Lothian was shut
after complaints from members of the local Trojan Swimming Club.
Traces of the probable cause, _Pseudomonas aeruginosa_, were discovered in
initial tests at the council-run pool. Environmental health officials from
West Lothian Council ordered the closure of the pool in Lanrigg Road,
Fauldhouse, as a precautionary measure. Council officers are now carrying
out further tests, and the pool will remain closed until the results have
been received which give the pool the all-clear. That is expected to happen
tomorrow at the earliest.
The closure of the Fauldhouse pool is the latest bug scare to hit West
Lothian's swimming baths in recent years. Swimmers at Bubbles Leisure Pool
in Livingston contracted the potentially deadly _Cryptosporidium_ protozoan
in 2002.
Fauldhouse councillor Neil Findlay said he was satisfied that all the
necessary safety steps had been taken by the council. He said: "The
swimming pool has been closed as a precautionary measure. The pool manager
acted quickly and responsibly. Environmental health officers are carrying
out a thorough investigation and the pool will not reopen until the test
results are satisfactory. It is an unfortunate situation, particularly for
swimming clubs, but I am sure the people of Fauldhouse will understand that
public health must take priority."
_Pseudomonas aeruginosa_ is a bacterium which flourishes in warm, moist
areas, making pools and hot tubs an ideal environment for it. The
bacterium is capable of causing significant illnesses including skin
rashes, an ear infection commonly known as swimmer's ear, urinary tract
infections, pneumonia, and corneal ulcers. It is the most common bacteria
found in skin rashes and ear infections associated with recreational
waters. It is associated with skin infections involving a mild to
moderate red, itchy rash. These rashes are often mistaken for chicken pox.
A West Lothian Council spokesman said: "Initial results of tests carried
out on pool water indicate possible bacterial contamination. _Pseudomonas
aeruginosa_ can cause skin and ear infections. Anyone displaying these
symptoms after swimming should consult their GP. Further tests are being
carried out and the results are not expected until Fri, 2 Apr 2004. It is
hoped that these results will be clear and the pool will be open for the
weekend."
