[Pseudomonas folliculitis (1) is a community-acquired skin infection
resulting from the bacterial infection of hair follicles following exposure
to contained, contaminated water, e.g., whirlpools (2), swimming pools (3
and as in this posting), hot tubs (3), and water slides (4). Initially
reported in the mid-1970s in association with whirlpool contamination, it
is caused by strains of _Pseudomonas aeruginosa_ acquired by skin
contamination of water containing the bacterium.
The rash has also been described in conjunction with the use of diving
suits (5) in both seawater and fresh water immersion, and even following
the use of contaminated bathing objects (such as a sponge) (6). Pseudomonas
folliculitis has occurred after skin depilation and without recognizable
exposure. Hot water, high pH (>7.8), and low chlorine level (<0.5 mg/L) all
predispose to infection.
This ubiquitous bacterium, _P. aeruginosa_, is found in soil and fresh
water and is able to obtain entry through hair follicles or via breaks in
the skin. Bacterial serotype O:11 is the most commonly reported isolate for
water-associated pseudomonas folliculitis, but other serotypes that have
been reported include O:1, O:3, O:4, O:6, O:7, O:9, O:10, and O:16.
The onset of this entity is usually 48 hours (range, 8 hrs to 5 days) after
exposure to contaminated water, but it has been reported to occur as long
as 14 days after exposure. Lesions begin as pruritic, erythematous macules
progressing to papules and pustules. The rash usually clears spontaneously
in 2-10 days and rarely recurs. It heals without scarring but may cause
desquamation or leave hyperpigmented macules.
Other symptoms that can occur with the rash include low-grade fever,
headache or malaise/fatigue. Otitis externa (swimmer's ear) may occur as
well. Breast tenderness in both women and men may also occur. The glands
of Montgomery on the nipple may become infected or overt mastitis may
develop. Named after William Fetherstone H. Montgomery, they are a group of
12-15 sebaceous glands in the areola of the nipple that produce small
prominences around the nipple of the breast that enlarge during pregnancy
and lactation, having the appearance of small seedlike tubercles. They were
previously described by Giovanni Battista Morgagni of _Morganella morgagni_
fame. In immunocompromised (particularly neutropenic) patients, lesions
can progress to ecthyma gangrenosum (7).
1. Gustafson TL, Band JD, Hutcheson RH, Schaffner W. Pseudomonas
folliculitis: an outbreak and review. Rev Infect Dis 1983;5:1-8.
2. Baruchini AN, Shapira A, Scharf S, Rosenberg L. Pseudomonas
folliculitis acquired from hot tubs and whirlpools:an overview. Ann Burns
Fire Disasters. 1996;9.
3. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Pseudomonas
dermatitis/folliculitis associated with pools and hot tubs - Colorado and
Maine - 1999-2000. MMWR 2000; 49:1087-1090.
4. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. An outbreak of Pseudomonas
folliculitis associated with a waterslide - Utah. MMWR 1983;32:425-7.
5. Saltzer KR, Schutzer PJ, Weinberg JM, et al. Diving suit dermatitis: a
manifestation of Pseudomonas folliculitis. Cutis 1997; 59:245-6.
6. Frenkel LM. Pseudomonas folliculitis from sponges promoted as beauty
aids. J Clin Microbiol 1993; 31: 2838.
7. El Baze P, Thyss A, Caldani C, et al. Pseudomonas aeruginosa O-11
folliculitis. Development into ecthyma gangrenosum in immunosuppressed
patients. Arch Dermatol 1985; 121: 873-6.
- Mod.LL]
